WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.480
Before you ever pick up a phone, I need you
to understand something.

2
00:00:04.940 --> 00:00:09.500
Every lead sitting in our CRM is a real
person going through something real.

3
00:00:09.820 --> 00:00:13.240
They're not a number. They're not a hot lead
or a cold lead.

4
00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:15.860
They're a person with a house and a problem.

5
00:00:15.860 --> 00:00:20.620
If you understand what they're going through
before you call, you're going to have

6
00:00:20.620 --> 00:00:27.040
better conversations, build more trust, and
close more deals than someone who just dials

7
00:00:27.040 --> 00:00:29.140
and wings it. That's not a guess.

8
00:00:29.440 --> 00:00:31.640
That's what we've seen over and over again.

9
00:00:31.640 --> 00:00:34.340
Not every homeowner is someone we can help.

10
00:00:34.840 --> 00:00:39.420
We're looking for a specific type of seller,
someone who has a property they need to

11
00:00:39.420 --> 00:00:44.240
sell, and a situation where going the
traditional route just doesn't make sense for

12
00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:47.860
them. Here are the situations we see most
often.

13
00:00:49.060 --> 00:00:54.000
Inherited property. Someone passes away and
leaves a house to their kids or their

14
00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:57.440
relatives. Those relatives often live in a
different city.

15
00:00:57.740 --> 00:00:59.340
They don't want to manage the property.

16
00:00:59.820 --> 00:01:01.480
They don't have money for repairs.

17
00:01:01.540 --> 00:01:05.160
And they don't want to fly in and deal with
tenants or contractors.

18
00:01:05.360 --> 00:01:06.960
They just want it handled.

19
00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:12.180
This is one of our biggest lead sources, and
these conversations tend to be emotional,

20
00:01:12.640 --> 00:01:13.980
so be ready for that.

21
00:01:14.980 --> 00:01:18.500
Financial pressure. Behind on mortgage
payments.

22
00:01:19.100 --> 00:01:22.800
Facing pre-foreclosure or actual
foreclosure.

23
00:01:23.320 --> 00:01:28.520
Tax liens piling up. They need to sell fast
to stop the bleeding.

24
00:01:28.860 --> 00:01:34.700
Going the traditional route, listing it,
staging it, waiting for a buyer, waiting for

25
00:01:34.700 --> 00:01:37.360
financing to clear. That takes months.

26
00:01:37.920 --> 00:01:40.180
These sellers don't have months.

27
00:01:41.060 --> 00:01:46.020
Tired landlords. They bought a rental property
years ago thinking it would be passive

28
00:01:46.020 --> 00:01:52.080
income. Now they've got bad tenants who won't
pay, maintenance issues every other week,

29
00:01:52.640 --> 00:01:56.080
vacancies eating into their savings, and
they're just done.

30
00:01:56.560 --> 00:01:58.840
They've hit a wall and they want out.

31
00:01:59.180 --> 00:02:02.220
You'll hear a lot of sighing on these calls.

32
00:02:03.080 --> 00:02:06.920
Property condition. The house needs major
work.

33
00:02:07.580 --> 00:02:13.800
Roof, foundation, mold, fire damage,
hoarding situations.

34
00:02:14.420 --> 00:02:20.560
It can't be listed on the MLS in its current
condition, and the seller can't afford the

35
00:02:20.560 --> 00:02:22.040
repairs to get it there.

36
00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:27.840
We buy it as is, which is exactly what they
need to hear.

37
00:02:29.060 --> 00:02:34.660
Divorce. When couples decide to part ways,
selling their home can become a pressing

38
00:02:34.660 --> 00:02:39.800
issue. Emotions run high, and the urgency to
sell often increases.

39
00:02:40.400 --> 00:02:46.320
As the neutral party, your role is to
facilitate a smooth sale, make sure both parties

40
00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:50.200
feel heard and respected, and help them move
forward.

41
00:02:51.040 --> 00:02:53.940
And sometimes, life just happens.

42
00:02:54.580 --> 00:02:59.380
A job relocation on short notice, health
issues that mean they can't maintain the

43
00:02:59.380 --> 00:03:04.740
property anymore, a death in the family,
downsizing because the house is too much to

44
00:03:04.740 --> 00:03:09.320
handle. These situations create urgency and
emotional complexity.

45
00:03:09.800 --> 00:03:14.720
The seller needs simplicity and speed, and
someone who's not going to make it harder.

46
00:03:15.620 --> 00:03:17.180
Out-of-state owners.

47
00:03:17.960 --> 00:03:22.960
They own a property in one of our markets,
but they live somewhere else entirely.

48
00:03:23.640 --> 00:03:26.120
Managing it from a distance is a headache.

49
00:03:26.260 --> 00:03:30.780
They might have a property manager eating
into whatever rent they're collecting, or the

50
00:03:30.780 --> 00:03:32.220
place might be sitting vacant.

51
00:03:32.480 --> 00:03:35.580
They want to cash out without having to deal
with any of it.

52
00:03:36.260 --> 00:03:40.180
Now here's the distinction you need to make
on every single call.

53
00:03:40.780 --> 00:03:44.460
Is this person motivated to sell, or are
they just curious?

54
00:03:45.320 --> 00:03:49.020
A motivated seller has a reason and a
timeline.

55
00:03:49.860 --> 00:03:52.880
They don't just want to sell someday, when
the stars align.

56
00:03:53.560 --> 00:03:54.920
They need to sell soon.

57
00:03:55.640 --> 00:03:57.140
There's something pushing them.

58
00:03:57.460 --> 00:03:59.640
Financial pressure? A deadline?

59
00:04:00.640 --> 00:04:03.080
An emotional weight they can't carry
anymore?

60
00:04:04.140 --> 00:04:07.240
An unmotivated seller is just exploring.

61
00:04:07.960 --> 00:04:12.320
They'd sell if someone walked up and offered
them full retail, but there's no real

62
00:04:12.320 --> 00:04:16.940
urgency, no pain, no reason to accept a
discounted offer.

63
00:04:17.360 --> 00:04:22.080
These people will waste your time if you let
them, so you need to learn to tell the

64
00:04:22.080 --> 00:04:23.040
difference fast.

65
00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:27.840
The tricky part is that motivation isn't
always obvious.

66
00:04:28.620 --> 00:04:33.220
Sometimes the seller says, I'm just seeing
what you'd offer, and underneath that,

67
00:04:33.580 --> 00:04:38.340
they're three months behind on payments and
too embarrassed to say it out loud to a

68
00:04:38.340 --> 00:04:39.420
stranger on the phone.

69
00:04:39.740 --> 00:04:44.100
That's where good questions come in, and
we'll get into that in a later section.

70
00:04:45.100 --> 00:04:48.380
When you're on a call, listen for phrases
like these.

71
00:04:48.960 --> 00:04:50.920
They signal real motivation.

72
00:04:50.920 --> 00:04:54.700
I inherited this house and I don't know what
to do with it.

73
00:04:55.020 --> 00:04:56.700
I just need this off my plate.

74
00:04:56.820 --> 00:04:58.540
I can't afford to fix it up.

75
00:04:58.820 --> 00:05:03.840
I'm behind on payments, my tenants just
trashed the place, I'm going through a divorce,

76
00:05:03.980 --> 00:05:06.420
I'm moving and I need to sell fast.

77
00:05:06.700 --> 00:05:09.140
I've had it listed and it's not selling.

78
00:05:09.640 --> 00:05:11.540
I just want to be done with it.

79
00:05:12.260 --> 00:05:17.100
When you hear language like that, you're
probably talking to someone we can help.

80
00:05:17.660 --> 00:05:20.560
Pay attention to it. Write it down in your
notes.

81
00:05:21.980 --> 00:05:27.380
There are also situations where we can't
help, and you need to recognize those too, so

82
00:05:27.380 --> 00:05:30.600
you're not spending time on leads that
aren't going anywhere.

83
00:05:30.940 --> 00:05:35.940
If they've got an active listing agreement
with a Realtor, we generally can't work that

84
00:05:35.940 --> 00:05:38.060
deal unless they're willing to cancel.

85
00:05:38.060 --> 00:05:42.960
If the person on the phone isn't actually
the owner, or they can't make the decision to

86
00:05:42.960 --> 00:05:47.860
sell because there's a trust involved or
multiple family members who all have to agree,

87
00:05:48.200 --> 00:05:49.600
you need to figure that out early.

88
00:05:50.260 --> 00:05:55.440
If there's no equity, and they owe more than
the property is worth, with no creative

89
00:05:55.440 --> 00:05:58.580
deal structure possible, it's probably not a
fit.

90
00:05:58.880 --> 00:06:04.020
And if it's a commercial building or vacant
land, that's outside what we do.

91
00:06:04.020 --> 00:06:07.660
Here's the thing I really want to stick with
you from this section.

92
00:06:08.680 --> 00:06:13.740
Before you call a seller, think about what
it's like to be on the other end.

93
00:06:14.200 --> 00:06:19.560
These sellers are getting five, sometimes
ten calls a day from people just like you.

94
00:06:20.040 --> 00:06:25.500
Every cold caller, every investor, every We
Buy Houses company is hitting the same list.

95
00:06:25.760 --> 00:06:30.320
By the time that seller gets to you, they've
already answered the same questions from

96
00:06:30.320 --> 00:06:31.400
multiple strangers.

97
00:06:31.400 --> 00:06:36.860
They're skeptical, they're tired of the
calls, some of them are borderline hostile

98
00:06:36.860 --> 00:06:37.860
because of it.

99
00:06:38.860 --> 00:06:42.000
Your job is to be different from all those
other callers.

100
00:06:42.060 --> 00:06:47.740
Not by having a slicker pitch or a faster
talk track, by actually listening.

101
00:06:48.300 --> 00:06:51.960
By taking the time to understand what's
going on in their life.

102
00:06:52.320 --> 00:06:55.660
By treating them like a human being instead
of a transaction.

103
00:06:55.660 --> 00:07:00.860
The sellers who end up closing with us don't
do it because we offered the most money.

104
00:07:01.380 --> 00:07:04.780
We usually don't. They close with us because
they trust us.

105
00:07:05.020 --> 00:07:09.960
And that trust starts right here, with
understanding who they are and what they're going

106
00:07:09.960 --> 00:07:12.200
through, before you ever say hello.

107
00:07:13.520 --> 00:07:14.460
You're doing great!

108
00:07:15.440 --> 00:07:18.720
Next up, you'll meet a few of these sellers
face to face.

109
00:07:19.080 --> 00:07:19.840
I'll see you there.
